'''''Hermann''''' was a [[Kriegsmarine]] [[weather ship]] that was built in 1929 as the [[fishing trawler]] '''''J. F. Schröder'''''. She was renamed '''''Sachsen''''' in 1933 and requisitioned in 1940, serving as '''''WBS 1 Sachsen'''''. She was renamed ''Hermann'' in 1942, serving until scuttled off the coast of Greenland in June 1943.
==Description== The ship was {{convert|140|ft|1|in|m|2|disp=flip}} long, with a beam of {{convert|24|ft|4|in|m|2|disp=flip}}. She had a depth of {{convert|12|ft|5|in|m|2|disp=flip}}. The ship was powered by a six-cylinder [[four-stroke engine|four stroke]] single cycle, single action [[diesel engine]] which drove a single screw propeller. Rated at 183[[nominal horsepower|nhp]], it was built by [[MAN SE|Maschinenfabrik Augsburg-Nürnburg]], [[Augsburg]]. She wasassessed as {{GRT|284}}, {{NRT|106}}.<ref name=JFS30>{{cite web |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=30a0317.pdf |title=Lloyd's Register, Trawlers &c. |author=Lloyd's of London |year=1930 |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>
==History== ''J. F. Schröder'' was built in 1929 as [[yard number]] 235 by Schiffbau-Gesellschaft Unterweser [[Aktiengesellschaft|AG]], [[Wesermünde]] for the Deutsche Hochsee Fischerei Bremen-Cuxhaven AG. She was launched in June 1929, and completed the next month.<ref name=miramar>{{csr|register=MSI|id=26947 |shipname=J.F.Schroder |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> Her port of registry was [[Cuxhaven]] and the [[Code Letters]] RHJP,<ref name=JFS30/> and fishing registration HC&nbsp;214 were allocated.<ref name=Warcovers>{{cite web |url=http://www.warcovers.dk/greenland/wbs1_1.htm |title=Wetterbeobachtungs-Schiff Sachsen WBS 1 |publisher=Warcovers |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> In 1933, she was renamed ''Sachsen''.<ref name=JFS33>{{cite web |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=33a0289.pdf |title=Lloyd's Register, Navires a Vapeur et a Moteurs de moins de 300 tx, Chalutiers &c. |author=Lloyd's of London |year=1933 |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> With the change of Code Letters in 1934, ''Sachsen'' was allocated the letters DICM.<ref name=S34>{{cite web |url=http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=34a0475.pdf |title=Lloyd's Register, Navires a Vapeur et a Moteurs de moins de 300 tx, Chalutiers &c. |author=Lloyd's of London |year=1933 |publisher=Plimsoll Ship Data |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>
On 22 May 1940, ''Sachsen'' was requisitioned by the [[Kriegsmarine]]. She was converted to a [[weather ship]] and was commissioned on 18 September. She had a crew of fifteen, plus five meteorologists. From 18 September to 23 November, she was employed on a mission to the [[Denmark Strait]]. In the spring and summer of 1941, she operated off the Norwegian island of [[Jan Mayen]]. On 10 October 1941, ''Sachsen'' sailed from [[Tromsø]], Norway with {{ship|German weather ship|WBS 4 Fritz Homann||2}} for Jan Mayen, where an automatic weather station was to be established. This was completed on 29 October and the two ship departed from Jan Mayen on 15 November.<ref name=Warcovers/>
''Sachsen'' was later renamed ''Hermann''.<ref name=Warcovers/> On 22 August 1942 she sailed from Tromsø to operate off the east coast of Greenland, arriving at [[Shannon Island]] on 27 August. The ship was disguised in an attempt to make her look like sea ice. In the spring of 1943, the Germans were discovered by the ''[[Slædepatruljen Sirius]]'', but they later managed to capture its leader, and ordered him to help them find a new site for a weather station. He took Kapitän Ritter to [[Scoresbysund]], where Ritter was captured by the Allies and made a [[prisoner of war]].<ref name=Arctic>{{cite web |url=http://d-dayforecast.com/contents/arctic-weather-war/ |title=Arctic Weather Warriors |first=John |last=Rees |publisher=d-dayforecast.com |accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> ''Hermann'' was scuttled on 17 June 1943 in Hansa Bay. Her crew were evacuated by a [[Dornier Do 26]] [[flying boat]].<ref name=Warcovers/>
